@John

(All?) smartwatches have the option to display an analog-like face with hands. I get your nit but I think the clue still holds. My problem with it was that for a moment I forgot what you called "wskazówki" in English 🤣 - our name for watch hands literally translates as "pointers" ("wskazywać" means "to point"; "wskazówka" also means "a hint").

Speaking of which - my car has a fully digital dashboard display, yet the odometer is styled to look like its old-school, analog ancestor. It even imitates the number drums turning slowly as you add another kilometer to your total distance traveled. It's pretty cool 😃

@John

I've only ever read one short story collection by Dukaj, and it was 10 or 15 years ago so I can't really remember his style. However, I've just looked at an excerpt from "Lód" ("Ice") and I can see how a translator would find it a challenge. The language is styled after Polish of the turn of the 19th and 20th centuries, both in vocabulary and syntax, but it obviously carries the author's idiosyncrasy, too. I must admit I find reading it tiresome - I prefer the refined simplicity of Olga Tokarczuk's prose - her mastery of the language is such she doesn't have to rely on cheap stylistic tricks, like "ye olde-ing" the shizzle out of everything. Reading her "Księgi Jakubowe" I was transported to the 18th century even though the language that got me there was essentially modern.

Inspired by previous conversations on this board I compared the originals and translations of other Polish authors, including Stanisław Lem and Henryk Sienkiewicz. In all cases the spirit of the original was lost, English not really being able to convey the sorts of things that are possible in Polish.

